around sunset,

34:04.476 --> 34:07.502
Southern <i>Cross</i> logged that
they'd lost visual contact

34:07.579 --> 34:10.047
with <i>the Sword of Orion
right around here.</i>

34:10.114 --> 34:11.446
Two hours later,

34:11.516 --> 34:14.076
<i>Practical Knowledge had
lost sight of them as well.</i>

34:14.152 --> 34:16.120
They tacked east
working off a report

34:16.187 --> 34:19.088
that called for 40-knot winds
out of the south-southwest.

34:19.157 --> 34:22.353
They were right here when
all their on board computers,

34:22.427 --> 34:25.886
including the SatNav radar,
malfunctioned.

34:25.964 --> 34:27.898
And not only did they not know
where they were,

34:27.966 --> 34:31.425
they had no way of knowing that the call for
40-knot winds was off by more than half.

34:31.503 --> 34:33.402
So, it was a few minutes
past midnight --

34:33.471 --> 34:35.803
Hey, Jeremy, did, uh,
something happen on this trip

34:35.873 --> 34:38.103
you want to talk about?
Something happen at home?

34:38.176 --> 34:40.076
No. Just my parents
are getting divorced.

34:40.145 --> 34:41.112
I know.

34:41.179 --> 34:43.079
So, I mean, it is what it is.

34:43.148 --> 34:44.616
Yeah.

34:44.683 --> 34:46.879
Anyway, it was a few minutes
past midnight

34:46.952 --> 34:48.920
when the <i>Sword</i> of <i>Orion</i>
turned again,

34:48.987 --> 34:50.955
making a course
for 82 degrees south,

34:51.022 --> 34:54.889
and that was the last mistake
they'd have a chance to make.

34:54.960 --> 34:56.893
